div.span:
The final analytics base table demonstrates the corresponding injection information for every production well.
Each row represents information for a single production well's
(the one that collects the bitumen mixture)

data in a single day.
The days in final base table must include the Date feature in Production Data, along with the Date features in the Well Testing Data and Injection Data.
Note there is overlap in the Wellfeaturein the Production Data and Well Testing Data, but not with the Injection Data. This is obviously because of the unique, one-to-many SAGD process.
The blue section represents the metered steam levels of all the injector wells in the field, although not all of them communicate with the specific production well. Anyways, all the metered steam data will be recorded as per the Production Data Date feature, NOT the production well and pad names!
The purple section represents the name of the production well/pad, it's pump speed, and sensor information for that particular date.
The green section refers to how much oil, water, and fluid (etc.) was collected by the production well on that particular day. There might not always be data here since well testing didn't happen every day (only happened sometimes) There is a test flag to indicate this binary nature.
The pink section represents the average temperature along a specific spatial segment of the liner for specific day. This is condensed from an initially much larger dataset.

switch.text: The final analytics base table demonstrates the corresponding injection information for every production well....

Hence, there is well overlap between testing data and production data.
